Next is Guided Access. We set out to make the most accessible devices of anyone for all of our customers. And we\xe2\x80\x99re really proud of how the accessibility community has been adopting iOS devices. Now, we\xe2\x80\x99ve been surprised by the number of children with autism who have been flocking to our devices, especially our iPads. And we want to make that experience even better.
There are a lot of great apps on the App Store like this one that are designed specifically for children with autism. The problem is there are some controls, some settings and other controls in the app that you don\xe2\x80\x99t want the child to tap while they\xe2\x80\x99re using the app. So Guided Access allows you just circle those controls with your finger, we\xe2\x80\x99ll figure out which ones you mean and we\xe2\x80\x99ll disable those controls for you. The child now can use the app without accidentally hitting those. And we lock the device into a single app mode, so hitting the home button doesn\xe2\x80\x99t leave the app.
Guided Access is great. It allows children with autism to learn independently on their iPad. Now this is great beyond children with autism. It\xe2\x80\x99s really single app mode and single app mode has a lot of applications. There are a lot of schools who\xe2\x80\x99ve been adopting iPads and some are starting to actually administer tests on their iPads. Well single app mode allows the teacher to lock that iPad into the test so the students can\xe2\x80\x99t go look up the answers in Safari. And this also works great for museums who use iPads and iPod touches for guided tours, so single app mode in Guided Access.
